  <body>
    <segment id="1" parent="17" relname="span">Microsoft just introduced an interesting error recovery feature for Windows XP.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="12" relname="circumstance"> Previously, when XP encountered a system error or serious application error</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="13" relname="span"> it would pop up a dialog box asking the user if he/she would like report the error to Microsoft.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="12" relname="elaboration"> If you clicked on &quot;Yes&quot; it would prepare and send an error report to Microsoft over the Internet.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="14" relname="span"> Microsoft has now introduced an OS patch that finds any material related to the error and displays it for the user.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="15" relname="span"> To quote the Microsoft website: </segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="5" relname="elaboration">
This update will enable you to automatically view responses to Windows error reports. After submitting an error report, if information relating to the crash event is available such as a fix, workaround, or other information, then the response may be viewed immediately and automatically. 
The patch is available for download at: 
http://www.microsoft.com/downloads/details.aspx?FamilyID=a1c6c3d8-5053-436e-b898-9cd995292baa&amp;DisplayLang=en </segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="11" relname="span">
It doesn&apos;t respond for all errors reported</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="9" relname="elaboration"> (I may just have unique errors),</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="10" relname="span"> but occasionally it returns useful information.</segment>
